Load Datasets

The data consist of the past 12 months from the Cyclistic bike-share program (https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html). Each month consists of 13 columns, and various number of rows due to rideship varying from each month.

Below is a brief explanation of the columns:

  • ride_id: id for each ride
  • rideable_type: type of bike the riders can choose from
  • started_at: when the ride started at
  • ended_at: when the ride ended at
  • start_station_name: where the ride started from
  • start_station_id: id of the start station
  • end_station_name: where the ride ended at
  • end_station_id: id of the end station
  • start_lat: latitude of the start station
  • start_lng: longitude of the start station
  • end_lat: latitude of the end station
  • end_lng: longitude of the start station
  • member_casual: rider is either a member or a casual rider

Clean and add data for analysis

Add columns to list day, month, and year of each ride

  • The “date” column is taking solely the date data from the date-time.
  • The “month”, “day”, and “year” columns are pulling their respective data from the date column.
  • The “weekday” column is converting the date into the respective weekday
  • The “hhmmss”, “hhmm” and “hh” columns take the hour, minute, and seconds data from the started_at column
all_trips$date <- as.Date(all_trips$started_at)
all_trips$month <- format(all_trips$date, "%m")
all_trips$day <- format(all_trips$date, "%d")
all_trips$year <- format(all_trips$date, "%Y")
all_trips$weekday <- format(all_trips$date, "%A")
all_trips$hhmmss <- format(all_trips$started_at, format="%H:%M:%s")
all_trips$hhmm <- format(all_trips$started_at, format="%H:%M")
all_trips$hh <- format(all_trips$started_at, format="%H")
all_trips$endhh <- format(all_trips$ended_at, format="%H")

Compute the distance using haversine formula with the lat/long for start/end

Although it is a stretch to look at the distance of each ride given the lack of tracking data from each bike ride, I thought it would be interesting to look at how potentially far each ride went. Using the haversine formula, I took the start lat/lng and end lat/lng data to determine how far each ride went.

my_dist <- function(long1, lat1, long2, lat2) {
  rad <- pi/180
  a1 <- lat1*rad
  a2 <- long1*rad
  b1 <- lat2*rad
  b2 <- long2*rad
  dlon <- b2 - a2
  dlat <- b1 - a1
  a <- (sin(dlat/2))^2 + cos(a1)*cos(b1)*(sin(dlon/2))^2
  c <- 2*atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))
  R <- 6378137
  d <- R*c
  m <- round(d/1600, digits = 2)
  return(m)
}

# Creating column for haversine computation
all_trips$distHav <- my_dist(all_trips$start_lng, all_trips$start_lat,
                             all_trips$end_lng, all_trips$end_lat)

Filter and sort data

To filter out all the data that would hurt the analysis, I filtered the data to not include start_station_names with the value of “WATSON TESTING - DIVVY”, and ride_length and distHav that were less than 0, since we do not want negative values.

# Filter out data that ruins analysis and sort by yyyy-mm-dd and hh:mm:ss
all_trips_sorted <- filter(all_trips, !(start_station_name=="WATSON TESTING - DIVVY" | ride_length<0 | distHav<0)) %>% 
  arrange(year, month, day, hhmmss)

Descriptive analysis

The ultimate goal of this case study is “How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?”
Below I ask several questions to see how different members and casual riders are through August 2020-July 2021, and have provided visuals in certain instances to highlight key information.

QUESTION: Examining difference in number of rides per month

To begin, I wanted to look at the number of rides per month by members and casual riders, and the average duration of each ride. The first piece of code gives a summary view of the number of rides and average duration by members and casual riders per month. The second piece of code shows a visual of that summary.

# number of rides per month
all_trips_sorted %>% 
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(started_at, label=TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(member_casual, month) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n(), avg_duration=mean(ride_length)) %>% 
  arrange(member_casual)

#### Analysis: * Casual ridership dips well below 100,000 rides from November through February * Casual ridership steadily increases from March throughout the summer, hitting its peak in July * Member ridership fell in the same time period, but remained much higher compared * Member ridership is higher compared to casual ridership most months (excluding June and July) * overall, members have a higher number of rides throughout the year, but casual ridership is higher during the summer months

QUESTION: Looking at difference in number of rides per month by day

The next question to look into was whether there was a difference in the number of rides by day in each month. The pieces of code provide a visual of the percentage of rides by day in each month.

# number of rides per month by day (graph)
num_rides_dow <-all_trips_sorted %>% 
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(started_at, label=TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(member_casual, month, day) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n(), avg_duration=mean(ride_length)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=day, y=number_of_rides, fill=member_casual, shape = member_casual)) + 
  geom_col(position="fill") + 
  facet_wrap(~month) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
num_rides_dow +
  labs(title="Number of Rides (%) per Month by Day") + xlab("Day") + ylab("Number of Rides") +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Rider Type"))

Analysis:

  • Member ridership is higher the majority of days throughout each month
  • Casual ridership follows a pattern of being higher every 7 days starting from late May to mid October
  • More information would be needed to determine if there is a weekday that experiences higher ridership between the two types of riders

Analysis:

  • Casual ridership during the winter months show hardly any activity
  • However, during late Spring-early Summer period, casual ridership experiences little activity in the morning but rises in the late afternoon
  • Member ridership experiences higher activity in the morning and late afternoon, but remains steady between the two periods

Summary

Overall, casual riders tend to ride for longer periods of time and shows higher number of rides on the weekends. The time data suggests that casual riders use the service for leisure due to the low usage in the morning and at night, which also suggests there are little number of casual riders that use it for getting to work. Also, casual ridership increases during the summer months, suggesting that when the weather warms up, casual ridership increases. Members tend to ride for shorter periods of time and show higher number of rides during the week. The time data suggests that members use it for work, due to the high usage in the morning and late afternoon. Also, member ridership remains high during most of the year, even though the winter months are understandably lower.

Recommendations

  • Casual riders tend to do more of their riding during the summer months (late May-early September)
  • Members tend to do most of their riding during the morning through the late afternoon
  • Casual riders tend to ride longer than members do
